Stephen,

In your example (testing an expensive external resource), here&#39;s how I&#39;d test it if I really didn&#39;t want to call it once per test (using JUnit 4, but this can be done in 3.8.1):

public class Foo {

   private static Object expensiveResult;
   private Object perTestExpensiveResultCopy;

   @BeforeClass 
   public static void performExpensiveCall() {
      // call expensive external resource and store result
     expensiveResult = externalResource.call();
   }

   // now for test isolation
   @Before
   public void setup() {
      perTestExpensiveResultCopy = expensiveResult.clone(); // or some such thing to copy it
   }

   @After
    public void cleanup() {
       // any necessary cleanup
       perTestExpensiveResultCopy = null;
    }

   @Test
    public void test1() {
       // use perTestExpensiveResultCopy
       assertTrue(...)
    }

   @Test
    public void test2() {
       // use perTestExpensiveResultCopy
       assertTrue(...)
    }
  }

A unit test should test one thing. Let&#39;s say you WANT to get multiple results. What&#39;s the UI for that? And besides the UI, what&#39;s even the point? We&#39;re trying to write tests in a way that requires nearly 0 human interaction. If you can get multiple results from a test, it seems you&#39;d need a person to process those results rather than the computer. It goes counter to AUTOMATION and moves towards more human intervention.

The original example was later answered well by someone else. Make testOrder() three tests instead of one. You get the results you want, though you do have to write a few more lines of code. The additional lines of code give you the chance to make your tests more self documenting. Imagine if, given the original example, it had instead been written:

public void testSuccess_ReverseOrder() {
   assertEquals( 9, Largest.largest( new int[] {9,8,7}));
}

public void testSuccess_InOrder() {
   assertEquals( 9, Largest.largest( new int[] {7, 8, 9}));
}

public void testSuccess_NoOrder() {
   assertEquals( 9, Largest.largest( new int[] {6, 3, 4 ,8, 9, 1, 2, 4, 5}));
}

public void testSuccess_MultipleLargest() {
   assertEquals( 9, Largest.largest( new int[] {6, 3, 4 ,8, 9, 1, 2, 9, 5}));
}

// Note, in the original test this assert would have failed. It should have been written
// in a way that would not fail but still assert what should happen
public void testFailure_DoesNotMatch() {
   assertNotEqual( 44, Largest.largest( new int[] {8,9,7}));
}

And so on... The name of the test states the intent of the test. I don&#39;t have to read the code to figure out the intention of what is being tested.

The original example should have been written as follows:
public void testOrder() {
   assertEquals( 9, Largest.largest( new int[] {9,8,7}));
   assertNotEqual( 44, Largest.largest( new int[] {8,9,7}));
   assertNotEqual( 32, Largest.largest( new int[] {7,8,9}));
}

Now I have seen cases where I have a long test with several asserts and I want to know what all is failing so I can fix them all. However:
This is not often a problem
It is more of a hassle than a problem
Fixing one thing might change the later results anyway, so there&#39;s no general way to address this problem
If it really is a hassle to keep rerunning my test, then maybe I need to refactor it so it is not so costly to run and test
What about the case where I have a server-side test? How about using Spring and IoC to make the test runnable inside or outside of a container?

I can think of a combination of things that would make this feature nice:
Existing system that I cannot change (too big, too political, ...)
Server-side test
Server takes a while to start up
I have to restart the sever every time I make a change
I have a big test with lots of asserts
In this situation, getting all the failures would be handy. If it really is a problem, I&#39;d consider writing some temporary scaffolding in support of the test. Say the test retrieves some object, makes changes and then performs validation. I&#39;d write some quick code to grab the object, serialize it, then write a test to test the serialized version of the object. Maybe I&#39;d even keep that test around. If I&#39;m worried about schema migration, either hard-code a serialVersionUID or use XML, or pick your externalization technology. I&#39;d make another test that gets to what I want to test that can run quickly.

Brett
